<subSubSection id="C38BD991B69C94B5B62561FC809D493C" pageNumber="382" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B6A2A9AD98C03D5C7E128ED6B1D80065" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis id="9900499D8C890CBDE374DC5EE5950C8F" italics="true" pageNumber="382">Note:</emphasis>
Although 
<normalizedToken id="B534F725CEE6E2B7856CCDA6084E2041" originalValue="D’Arcy">D'Arcy</normalizedToken>
&amp; Eshbaugh (in 
<emphasis id="D04C6DD43F5F6A4CB059673703D243B5" italics="true" pageNumber="382">Baileya</emphasis>
19: 98. 1974) discussed the type material, as has been pointed out by Janser. (
<emphasis id="8AAC369DC6C9CC15C22935EBAF59FEB4" italics="true" pageNumber="382">Spices, Condiments Med. Pl. Ethiopia</emphasis>
: 38. 1981), there is confusion as to which sheet was intended as type - the authors say that a Clifford sheet is the 
<typeStatus id="C384B13BD7AA593747AD400FEFA2665A">lectotype</typeStatus>
but also that it is on the IDC microfiche (i.e. = sheet 249.1 LINN). Janser. rejected both specimens in favour of a van Royen sheet in L. However, 
<normalizedToken id="1873F7D7F1514A0977F43CC831663CE5" originalValue="D’Arcy’s">D'Arcy's</normalizedToken>
later 1974 type statement is unequivocal, and has priority.
</paragraph>
